-- South African White, Yellow Corn Rises, Following U.S. Benchmark's Advance
-- B y   M k h u l u l i   M a n c o t y w a
-- 2010-09-30T07:36:20Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-09-30/south-african-white-yellow-corn-rises-following-u-s-benchmark-s-advance.html
Corn in South Africa, the largest
producer of the grain on the continent, rose after prices gained
in the U.S., which competes for African export markets.  Corn futures for December delivery rose 5 cents, or 1
percent, to $5.05 a bushel on the Chicago Board of Trade
yesterday. On Sept. 27, the most-active contract touched
$5.2875, the highest price since September 2008.  White corn for December delivery, the most active contract
on the South African Futures Exchange, added 19 rand, or 1.5
percent, to 1,270 rand ($181) a metric ton. Meal made from the
grain is the countryâ€™s staple food.  Yellow corn for December delivery gained 19 rand, or 1.4
percent, to 1,352 rand a ton. The grain is used mainly as animal
feed in South Africa.  Wheat for December delivery rose 27 rand, or 1 percent, to
2,635 rand a ton.  Gains or losses for the most active contracts of three
additional crops today were as follows. All prices are in rand
